Vec3f barycentric(std::array<Vec3f, 3> pts, Vec3f p) {
    const auto [a, b, c] = pts;

    const auto u = Vec3f(c.x - a.x, b.x - a.x, a.x - p.x) ^
                   Vec3f(c.y - a.y, b.y - a.y, a.y - p.y);

    // Degenerate triangle
    if (std::abs(u.z) < 1) {
        return Vec3f(-1, -1, -1);
    }

    return Vec3f(1.0 - (u.x + u.y) / u.z, u.y / u.z, u.x / u.z);
}

A simpler way to calculate the barycentric coordinates while staying in 2D is by using the signed area ratio method. Here's an example code for this approach:

```cpp
Vec3f barycentric_2D(std::array<Vec3f, 3> pts, Vec3f p) {
    const auto [a, b, c] = pts;

    float main_triangle_area = std::abs((b.x - a.x) * (c.y - a.y) - (c.x - a.x) * (b.y - a.y)) / 2;

    // Calculate areas of the subtriangles formed by point p
    float area_p_ab = std::abs((b.x - p.x) * (a.y - p.y) - (a.x - p.x) * (b.y - p.y)) / 2;
    float area_p_bc = std::abs((c.x - p.x) * (b.y - p.y) - (b.x - p.x) * (c.y - p.y)) / 2;
    float area_p_ca = std::abs((a.x - p.x) * (c.y - p.y) - (c.x - p.x) * (a.y - p.y)) / 2;

    // Calculate barycentric coordinates (u, v, w) as the ratio of the subtriangle areas to the main triangle area
    float u = area_p_bc / main_triangle_area;
    float v = area_p_ca / main_triangle_area;
    float w = 1 - u - v;

    return Vec3f(u, v, w);
}
```

In this version of the `barycentric_2D` function, we calculate the area of the main triangle defined by vertices (a, b, c), and the areas of the three subtriangles formed by point p and the triangle sides (pa, pb, pc).

The barycentric coordinates (u, v, w) are then calculated as the ratio of the corresponding subtriangle's area to the main triangle's area. This gives a more direct and intuitive understanding of barycentric coordinates. However, this approach uses more multiplications and divisions compared to the previous 3D cross product method.

Again, to check if the point `p` is inside the triangle using this function, call the `barycentric_2D` function and check if the returned `Vec3f` object has all its components greater or equal to 0 and their sum equal to 1. If this holds true, the point `p` lies inside the triangle.

Yes, you can compute the barycentric coordinates using the dot product. Here's an example code using the dot product for this approach:

```cpp
Vec3f barycentric_dot_product(std::array<Vec3f, 3> pts, Vec3f p) {
    const auto [a, b, c] = pts;

    // Compute vectors
    Vec3f v0 = b - a;
    Vec3f v1 = c - a;
    Vec3f v2 = p - a;

    // Compute dot products
    float dot00 = v0 * v0;
    float dot01 = v0 * v1;
    float dot02 = v0 * v2;
    float dot11 = v1 * v1;
    float dot12 = v1 * v2;

    // Compute barycentric coordinates (u, v, w)
    float invDenom = 1 / (dot00 * dot11 - dot01 * dot01);
    float u = (dot11 * dot02 - dot01 * dot12) * invDenom;
    float v = (dot00 * dot12 - dot01 * dot02) * invDenom;
    float w = 1 - u - v;

    return Vec3f(u, v, w);
}
```

In this version of the function, we calculate the two vectors formed between the points (vertices) of the triangle: `v0 = b - a` and `v1 = c - a`. We also calculate the vector between point `p` and vertex `a`: `v2 = p - a`. 

We then compute the dot products of these vectors. The dot products provide information about the projection of one vector onto another and the relative position of point `p` within the triangle.

Next, we calculate the barycentric coordinates (u, v, w) using the dot products we obtained. The inverse of the denominator `invDenom`, calculated from the dot products `dot00`, `dot01`, and `dot11`, normalizes the coordinates.

To check if the point `p` is inside the triangle using this function, call the `barycentric_dot_product` function and check if the returned `Vec3f` object has all its components greater or equal to 0 and their sum equal to 1. If these conditions hold, the point `p` lies inside the triangle.
